05363nam a22009255i 9781487530860DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875308607 a10.3138/97814875308602doi  a(DE-B1597)536654  a(OCoLC)1113866134  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aHIS0450002bisacsh04a860.9/3512231 aHernández, Rosilie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImmaculate Conceptions :bThe Power of the Religious Imagination in Early Modern Spain /cRosilie Hernández. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aToronto Iberic00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. The Anatomy of the Religious Imagination: Immaculacy and the Spanish Counter-Reformation -- t2. An Army of Peers: The Virgin of the Immaculate Conception for the Popular Imagination -- t3. Pintor Divino: The Painter as Divinely Inspired Liberal Artist and the Conditions of Representation for a Sacred Mystery -- t4. Visiones Imaginarias: Pacheco, Velázquez, Zurbarán, and Murillo -- t5. Concepción Maravillosa: Theological Discourse and Religious Women Writers -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aImmaculate Conceptions examines devotional writings, religious and literary texts, and visual art that feature the mystery of the immaculacy of the Virgin Mary in the culture of early modern Spain. The author’s analysis is motivated by the complexity and multivalent capacity of the doctrine and its icon at a time when the debates around Mary’s conception imbued all levels of religious and social life. She considers the many interests – political, doctrinal, artistic, and gender-driven – that intersect and compete in the exegesis and textual and visual representations of the Immaculate Conception. She argues that the Immaculate Conception of Mary proved to be a fertile conceptual and ideological field wherein the identities of the Spanish state, local communities, and individuals were negotiated, variously defined, and contested. The study’s broader aim is to delineate a speculative category, the religious imagination, defined as a spiritual, intellectual, or artistic pursuit in which the individual is committed to sacred truth yet articulates this truth through contingent, partial, and contextually determined theological propositions. The representational status of the image and its relationship to theories of physical sight and spiritual vision are central to the author’s formulation of this category.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 7aHISTORY / Europe / Spain & Portugal.2bisacsh  aCounter-Reformation.  aImmaculate Conception.  aSpain.  aSpanish.  aVirgin.  aearly modern.  aexperiences.  aimagination.  amystical.  apainting.  areligious.  asermons.  aseventeenth-century.  atheatre.  atheory of vision and sight.  atreatises.  avisionary.  awomen writers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019z9783110606195oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753086040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487530860423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487530860.jpg  a